   <mods:abstract>Referring to extraordinary expenses mentioned in Jefferson's letter of 15
            May 1788, Jay states that he has submitted the matter to Congress, but they seem
            disinclined to take any steps lest their approval of the expenditures offend their
            constituents. Little nobility can be expected from a government so constituted. Count de
            Moustier was well received, but now rumors are spread that his relationship with the
            Marchionesse is improper. Jay regrets this as she seems to be an amiable person, and he
            feels that if the Count were left to the exercise of his own judgment, he would think
            well of the United States.</mods:abstract>
